  "prompt": "What is the necessity of introducing 2000 rupee notes?",
  "response": "The introduction of the 2000 rupee note in India was primarily done in November 2016 as part of the demonetization initiative by the Indian government. Here are the key reasons behind its introduction:\n\n1. Replace high-value currency\n- To replace the older 1000 rupee notes that were demonetized\n- Provide a high-denomination note to facilitate large transactions\n\n2. Reduce cash handling\n- Decrease the number of physical currency notes in circulation\n- Make transactions more convenient for high-value purchases\n\n3. Combat black money\n- Make it difficult to hoard large amounts of unaccounted cash\n- Reduce the circulation of counterfeit currency\n\n4. Promote digital transactions\n- Encourage people to use digital payment methods\n- Reduce the dependence on physical cash\n\n5. Address logistical challenges\n- Manage cash flow during the demonetization period\n- Provide an alternative high-value currency denomination\n\nHowever, in September 2018, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) announced the gradual withdrawal of the 2000 rupee note from circulation, citing reduced demand and the goal of promoting digital transactions.\n\nThese reasons highlight the government's objectives of financial transparency, digitalization, and reducing black money through the introduction of the 2000 rupee note.",
